00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:10.340
CLAUDIO CHERUBINO:
Hi everyone.

00:00:10.340 --> 00:00:12.210
Welcome back to Google
Developers Live.

00:00:12.210 --> 00:00:14.400
My name is Claudio and I am one
of the engineers in the

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:16.280
Google Drive Developer
Relations Team.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:20.410
Today with me I have two special
guests, Austin and

00:00:20.410 --> 00:00:22.330
Sebastian from Cooliris.

00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:25.270
Austin is the co-founder
and CTO of Cooliris.

00:00:25.270 --> 00:00:28.390
And Sebastian works on Business

00:00:28.390 --> 00:00:29.780
Development, is that right?

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:30.260
SEBASTIAN MUEHL: Exactly.

00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:33.190
CLAUDIO CHERUBINO: Today they're
going to show us their

00:00:33.190 --> 00:00:36.630
app, Cooliris, which is, I would
say, visually stunning.

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:39.520
It's an amazing way to browse
your photos and do a lot of

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:40.500
other things.

00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:44.620
And I am pretty sure they can
explain it and show it much

00:00:44.620 --> 00:00:47.150
better than I could do.

00:00:47.150 --> 00:00:49.190
Austin, do you want to
show us what Cooliris

00:00:49.190 --> 00:00:50.720
does and what it is?

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:51.650
AUSTIN SHOEMAKER: I'd love to.

00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:56.850
So Cooliris is an app for mobile
devices and the web,

00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:59.880
which allows you to organize and
view all your media in a

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:05.019
unified experience, which allows
you to first access the

00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:06.000
media on your device.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.550
So here I'm accessing all
of the photos that are

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:10.740
stored on my tablet.

00:01:10.740 --> 00:01:13.850
All visible in this user
interface we've created that

00:01:13.850 --> 00:01:14.940
we call the Wall.

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:19.330
So the Wall actually allows me
to see everything and zoom

00:01:19.330 --> 00:01:21.860
into it and see the high
resolution content without the

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:24.490
need to leave the grid of
photos that I'm in.

00:01:24.490 --> 00:01:26.930
So that makes it much easier for
me to just come and zoom

00:01:26.930 --> 00:01:30.250
in and see one photo without
having to keep pressing the

00:01:30.250 --> 00:01:31.830
back button in the top left.

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:35.060
So I can browse content
from my camera roll.

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:38.980
And I can also link all of the
web services that I'm using.

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:45.630
So for example, we support
your device, Facebook,

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:51.170
Instagram, Twitter, Picasa,
Google+, Google Drive, Flickr.

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:54.360
And we just introduced
support for Renren

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:57.420
in China and SmugMug.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:00.250
You can also search Google
Images to find images.

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:04.260
And one of the big features that
you can take advantage of

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:07.930
in Cooliris is sharing any media
that you can browse with

00:02:07.930 --> 00:02:09.039
private groups.

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:11.690
So that enables you to start a
conversation around anything

00:02:11.690 --> 00:02:13.590
that you see.

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:16.500
And more than that, integrating
Google Drive has

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:19.980
enabled us to let you save
content from anywhere into

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:22.540
your Drive, which provides a
really great bridge between

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:24.820
your mobile device and
your computer.

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.850
So let me jump into Google Drive
and show you what that

00:02:27.850 --> 00:02:29.390
looks like.

00:02:29.390 --> 00:02:31.720
So all I do is tap on that
stack of photos.

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:35.170
And I'm already looking at all
of the media in my Drive.

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:37.890
So when we looked at, how do
we want to integrate Drive,

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:40.450
we're a very media-centric
experience, and so what we've

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:45.270
done is use the Google Drive
API to show you your photos

00:02:45.270 --> 00:02:48.380
that are stored in Drive in
reverse chronological order.

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:49.810
So these are the latest
photos that have

00:02:49.810 --> 00:02:51.170
been added to my Drive.

00:02:51.170 --> 00:02:54.660
And as I scroll, we actually
allow you to scroll through

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:58.250
all of the media that's
stored in Drive.

00:02:58.250 --> 00:03:01.760
And if I select a photo, it
actually will load the high

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:03.770
resolution version
of this photo.

00:03:03.770 --> 00:03:07.250
But that's where it starts to
become really cool that we're

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:09.480
able to take advantage
of the Drive API.

00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:15.580
So these images might be very
large JPEGs, or even more

00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:17.190
large files like RAW.

00:03:17.190 --> 00:03:19.470
Since Google Drive indexes
thumbnails, we're actually

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:22.130
able to request not only a small
thumbnail of the photo,

00:03:22.130 --> 00:03:24.610
which allows us to go through
the grid very quickly, but we

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:29.030
can also load the exact high
resolution representation

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:31.170
that's needed to display
it on your device.

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:34.680
So instead of loading a three or
four megabyte JPEG, we can

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:38.850
actually load exactly 300
kilobytes, which is enough to

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:40.180
show it on your--

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:42.610
And one of the really cool
things that we're able to do

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:44.120
is keep this up-to-date.

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:48.820
So the APIs that we're using to
populate the user interface

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:54.170
are the Drive files API, which
we use to pull in the files

00:03:54.170 --> 00:03:55.860
sorted by a date modified.

00:03:55.860 --> 00:04:01.600
And once we've loaded the
initial pages of files from

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:05.430
the files.get API, we then,
instead of refreshing that,

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:08.400
will pull the changes feed,
which gives us an ordered set

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:10.880
of changes to files that
are in your Drive.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:14.680
And by using files.get to
paginate out as you scroll

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:19.810
backward, and also using changes
list in order to get

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:22.600
the updates that have occurred
to what we've loaded, that

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:26.140
makes it very efficient for us
to show you a updated view of

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.030
content from your Drive
without pulling

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:29.760
everything up front.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:32.290
CLAUDIO CHERUBINO: So you're
using a number tricks here to

00:04:32.290 --> 00:04:35.950
have this very fast browsing
experience.

00:04:35.950 --> 00:04:38.640
So all already to
the Drive API.

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:43.030
First, you're downloading the
whole set the very first time,

00:04:43.030 --> 00:04:45.270
but then using the changes
feed to only get changes.

00:04:45.270 --> 00:04:45.440
And--

00:04:45.440 --> 00:08:43.820
[TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES]

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:45.440
AUSTIN SHOEMAKER: --in
that conversation.

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:47.860
CLAUDIO CHERUBINO:
That's very nice.

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:48.330
Thank you.

