00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:38.940
CLAUDIO CHERUBINO: Maybe you
couldn't find anything bad,

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:39.755
but maybe you did.

00:10:39.755 --> 00:10:41.980
AUSTIN SHOEMAKER: Oh, so when
we first integrated with the

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:45.030
version two API, which was the
first time we could really

00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:45.830
build our product.

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:48.900
In the version one API, you were
only able to store and

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:51.150
get files created by
the application.

00:10:51.150 --> 00:10:53.400
And in the version two API we're
able to request access

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:56.210
to all the files that are on
Drive, which is what we were

00:10:56.210 --> 00:10:58.400
able to build the Wall with.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:00.490
There's no image centric
metadata.

00:11:00.490 --> 00:11:01.910
And that's one of the things
that the Drive--

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:13.730
other image metadata, which
we're able to display in the

00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:17.350
little metadata bar
at the bottom.

00:11:17.350 --> 00:11:20.750
And there's no way that we could
actually display that to

00:11:20.750 --> 00:11:23.000
you without API assistance
because we'd

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:23.820
have to load the files.

00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:27.660
So the beautiful thing here is
that Drive API can stream us

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:28.860
the content that we need.

00:11:28.860 --> 00:11:31.190
First, the metadata, and then
the low resolution thumbnail,

00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:33.630
and then, on demand, the high
resolution content.

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:39.430
It was initially a limitation,
and then it was quickly

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:40.760
addressed in the API.

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:42.680
CLAUDIO CHERUBINO: You mentioned
the image metadata.

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:45.480
When we released the first
version API we got a lot of

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:47.580
requests about adding more
and more metadata to the

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:48.750
image and we did.

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:52.570
We added some of the
common Exif fields.

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:55.700
So what fields do you
actually surface?

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:58.990
I see you use file name,
and the file size,

00:11:58.990 --> 00:12:00.750
and width and height.

00:12:00.750 --> 00:12:05.420
Do you also use other fields,
like location or what camera

00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:06.750
took that photo, things
like that?

00:12:06.750 --> 00:12:08.300
Are those needed?

00:12:08.300 --> 00:12:10.420
AUSTIN SHOEMAKER: Yeah, so
right now, we don't show

00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:13.690
extended Exif metadata, like
camera make, model, et cetera.

00:12:13.690 --> 00:12:15.350
We'll probably add that
in the future.

00:12:15.350 --> 00:12:17.270
One of the ones we do use
today is location,

00:12:17.270 --> 00:12:18.320
which is very cool.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:21.840
So if your photo has geographic
coordinates, then

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:24.590
we get that information from
the Drive API and then we

00:12:24.590 --> 00:12:27.280
reverse geocode that into a
named location, which we

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:29.580
display in the metadata bar
when you select the photo.

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:32.500
So that's really great because
then you can get more context

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:33.400
for your media.

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:35.580
Instead of just seeing the
photo, you can see when and

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:36.970
where it was taken.

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:39.700
One feature that Drive
has always had--

00:12:39.700 --> 00:12:44.190
which is really cool and that
makes us look even more cool,

00:12:44.190 --> 00:12:46.500
although it's purely the
API doing this, I'd

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:48.460
